##  Microservices Details

###  Loan Microservice

- Runs on port **8081**
- Provides loan details based on loan number

**Endpoint:**

GET /loans/{number}


**Sample Response:**
```json
{
  "number": "H00987987972342",
  "type": "car",
  "loan": 400000,
  "emi": 3258,
  "tenure": 18
}
 Account Microservice
Runs on port 8080
Calls Loan microservice using RestTemplate

Endpoint:

GET /accounts/{number}

Sample Response:

{
  "accountNumber": "H00987987972342",
  "loanDetails": {
    "number": "H00987987972342",
    "type": "car",
    "loan": 400000,
    "emi": 3258,
    "tenure": 18
  }
}
## Communication Between Services
Account service calls Loan service using:
RestTemplate.getForObject()
Loan service must be running before calling Account service.

## Challenges Faced
Initial folder structure issues (nested folders)
Port conflicts between services
"Connection refused" error when Loan service was not running
Java file naming issue (public class must match file name)

## Key Learnings
Basics of microservices architecture
Creating REST APIs using Spring Boot
Inter-service communication using RestTemplate
Handling common runtime errors
Importance of proper project structure

## How to Run the Project
Run Loan Service on port 8081
Run Account Service on port 8080
Open browser and test:
http://localhost:8080/accounts/H00987987972342

Conclusion

This hands-on helped me understand how microservices interact with each other. I learned how to build independent services and connect them using REST APIs. I also gained experience in debugging common issues during development.